      "properties": {"text": ""},
      "widgets_values": [
        "ATLAS OCCLUSION MASK — TEST WORKFLOW\n\n1. Load your source photo in node ① (or use the example.jpg default).\n2. Generate ONE novel view of the same scene at a KNOWN named angle\n   (Qwen-Image-Edit-2511 + Multiple-Angles LoRA, e.g. via\n   ComfyUI-qwenmultiangle). This example assumes 'front-right quarter\n   view / eye-level shot / medium shot' from a straight-on 'front view'\n   source — the same angle used in the multiangle-patch-proof workflow.\n   Load it in node ④.\n\n2. CRITICAL — keep the named views IN SYNC across nodes ⑤ and ⑦:\n   patch_azimuth_view / patch_elevation_view / patch_distance /\n   source_azimuth_view / source_elevation_view / flip_azimuth must be\n   IDENTICAL on AtlasOcclusionMask and AtlasAddPatchView. They build the\n   SAME orbit camera independently (via the shared\n   _named_view_orbit_delta helper) — if the two nodes disagree, the mask\n   will not line up with the patch geometry it's supposed to describe.\n\n3. Queue. Check node ⑤'s two mask previews:\n   - 🕳 Occlusion Mask should be WHITE on grazing walls, backsides, and\n     anything outside the primary photo's frame — exactly the areas an\n     artist would expect the recovered camera couldn't have seen from\n     this new angle.\n   - ✅ Coverage Mask should be the visual inverse (white where the\n     primary already has good, head-on coverage).\n   If the white/black split looks backwards or nothing lines up with the\n   geometry, double check the named-view settings in step 2 first.\n\n4. Node ⑥ (ImageCompositeMasked) is a PLACEHOLDER here: destination and\n   source are both the same novel-view image, so it's a no-op — it only\n   proves the wiring runs end-to-end. In a real pipeline you'd swap in a\n   DIFFERENT destination or source (e.g. an independently inpainted/\n   refined image) so the mask actually selects between two different\n   images instead of compositing an image with itself.\n\n5. Nodes ⑦/⑧ run the normal AtlasAddPatchView -> Viewport check: hit\n   📷 Camera View, then 📽 Project, then orbit toward the patch angle —\n   it should fill in exactly the region the occlusion mask flagged white."
      ]
    }
